       Comparing the lived world with the
    ideal world, noted American philosophical naturalist, poet, and
    literary critic George Santayana (1863-1952) seeks in this
    influential compilation of his earlier works to outline the
    ancient ideal of a well-ordered life, one in which reason is
    the organizing force that recognizes the need to allocate
    science, religion, art, social concerns, and practical wisdom
    their proper role and appropriate emphasis within the fully
    developed human experience.**
    </p>
